[[File:Dahlia Moonfire 1.jpg|thumbnail|right|'Moonfire' ([[VanDusen Botanical Garden]], Stan Shebs)]] The following is a list of [[dahlia]] cultivars which have gained the [[Royal Horticultural Society]]'s [[Award of Garden Merit]]. They are [[tuberous]] [[perennial plant|perennial]]s, originally from South America, with showy daisy-like [[pseudanthium|composite]] flowerheads in all shades and combinations of white, yellow, orange, pink and red, flowering in late summer and autumn (fall). Much work has been done on the development of a range of flower shapes and sizes. They may be sold as dry tubers in Spring, and started off in heat before being planted out after all danger of frost has passed. Alternatively they can be purchased later in the season, in pots ready to flower. Dwarf [[bedding (horticulture)|bedding]] types are usually cultivated as [[annual plant|annual]]s and discarded after flowering. In mild areas without penetrating frosts, mature plants can be overwintered in the garden; otherwise, they are lifted and stored in a frost free place. They are easily propagated from cuttings in Spring.<ref name=RHSAZ>{{cite book|title=RHS A-Z encyclopedia of garden plants|year=2008|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|location=United Kingdom|isbn=1405332964|pages=1136}}</ref>
Flower shapes can be divided into [[Dahlia#Horticultural_classification|14 main groups]]:- #single: less than {{convert|10|cm|0|abbr=on}} - open centred, with a single or double row of ray florets #waterlily: miniature, small or medium sized blooms - double, with a small number of flattened, rounded ray florets #collerette: {{convert|10|-|15|cm|0|abbr=on}} - single row of flat ray florets surrounding an inner collar of shorter florets and a central disc #anemone-flowered: {{convert|10|-|15|cm|0|abbr=on}} - upward-pointing, tubular florets, surrounded by one or more rows of flattened ray florets #pompon: {{convert|10|cm|0|abbr=on}} - tightly spherical small blooms with florets in a scale-like arrangement #ball: similar to pompon but larger in size #semi-cactus: double flowers in a range of sizes; many pointed, recurved ray florets #cactus: double flowers in a range of sizes; many pointed, recurved ray florets that are narrower than semi-cactus flowers #decorative: fully double flowers with the central disc completely hidden; the broad florets may be pointed and twisted #miscellaneous: including peony-flowered, orchid-flowered, chrysanthemum-flowered, dwarf bedding
As of 2015, 124 cultivars are listed.{{sfn|RHS|2015|loc=[http://apps.rhs.org.uk/agm/Award2.asp?User2=Hrb&crit=Dahlia Search for AGM Plants: Dahlia]}} Maximum dimensions of plants are shown in centimetres.
